Quarto is a document preparation system. If you've never heard of it, it's sort of

00:00:11.760 --> 00:00:17.920
like the successor to R Markdown that sort of integrates blogs and presentations and

00:00:17.920 --> 00:00:24.160
documents and books. So I'll mostly be focused on how to use Shiny inside of Quarto. So I think

00:00:24.160 --> 00:00:28.400
the links will be in Slack, but here is the link to the slides. And then there'll be a link to a

00:00:28.400 --> 00:00:36.480
separate repo that has the example book. All right, so shinylive is both an R and Python.

00:00:38.160 --> 00:00:43.759
For R, there's a shinylive Quarto extension, as well as an R CRAN package that you can use.

00:00:44.320 --> 00:00:49.119
And what it does is it uses the WebAssembly version of R. And that's like a precompiled

00:00:49.119 --> 00:00:55.119
version of R that could be used in your browser and interfaced using JavaScript. So basically,

00:00:55.119 --> 00:01:00.799
we take R and packages that you're going to use in your Shiny app, we bundle them together in a

00:01:00.799 --> 00:01:08.639
big binary object, and then we use JavaScript in the browser to access that. So it's all done on

00:01:08.639 --> 00:01:13.519
your browser. It's all done on your iPhone or iPad or whatever you're using to access the website.

00:01:14.400 --> 00:01:17.199
There's links here for the Quarto extension in the R package.

00:01:19.199 --> 00:01:24.000
Oh, I should say that my goal here initially was, you write books on machine learning and

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:28.720
things like that. We want to show, for example, like how model complexity affects, let's say,

00:01:28.720 --> 00:01:33.599
classification models. And so what we'd like to, instead of having a ggplot with a bunch of facets,

00:01:33.599 --> 00:01:39.839
we'd like to have some shiny sliders that we can say, like, increase complexity and see what the

00:01:39.839 --> 00:01:46.320
results are in a plot. So that's really where I would like to go with this. So what you do is,

00:01:47.040 --> 00:01:51.680
when you're running your Quarto document, you basically create a code chunk that instead of

00:01:51.919 --> 00:01:58.800
Python has the type ShinyLive-R. And then all your app and UI stuff goes within that chunk.

00:01:58.800 --> 00:02:02.000
Now, the one thing that you do have to do is you have to give it an extra option,

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:07.680
standalone equal true. And that's just required to set everything up for ShinyLive to work.

00:02:07.680 --> 00:02:12.559
Another thing you have to do is in your main Quarto file, in the YAML, you have to add a filter

00:02:12.559 --> 00:02:15.600
for ShinyLive. And from there, it's kind of off to the races.

00:02:16.559 --> 00:02:21.360
Now, one thing that's, and I should say, a lot of this is currently in flux. Joe Chang did a great

